                        <tr>
                                <td colspan="2"><span class="postbody">I want to get hit by charm breaks.
<br />

<br />
I want to get hit by mez resists.
<br />

<br />
I want the benefit of charm/mez to be worth the risk of the enchanter getting hit.
<br />

<br />
Imagine if you couldn't avoid being hit by pets in Tipt/Vxed no matter what you did.
<br />

<br />
Now, given enchanter fragility, this means mez and charm have to be extremly powerful.
<br />

<br />
This isn't good for the game: because players who learn to mitigate the risks through various means end up with an overly powerful ability (see: tipt/vxed/geared LDoN hard pets).
<br />

<br />
So if we can't increase the reward (for game balance purposes), reduce the risk.
<br />

<br />
There are two ways of reducing the risk.  The first is making charmed pets/mezzed mobs hit the enchanter less often, anywhere from 'rarely' to 'only when the enchanter screws up'. <span style="font-style: italic">edit: added 'anywhere'</span>
<br />

<br />
The other way is to make the enchatner more durable.  A more durable enchanter who is expected to be hit somewhat frequently by mobs due to mez resists/charm breaks.  <span style="font-style: italic">(edited addition)</span> With a more durable enchanter, the OoW charm nerf would be more viable, in camp crowd control with it's resists would be far safer, and the game would feel more like old school seb and less like running around with your head cut off.
<br />

<br />
The solution in the original post of this thread falls under the "enchanter gets hit less often" category.  <span style="font-style: italic">(edited addition)</span> Hence, I don't like it.  =)</span><span class="postbody"></span><span class="gensmall"><br /><br />Last edited by Yakk on Thu Sep 30, 2004 10:40 am; edited 1 time in total</span></td>
                        </tr>
                </table></td>
        </tr>
