                        <tr>
                                <td colspan="2"><span class="postbody">I like these ideas, and while I would accept #1, combined with #3, I like the "debuff proc" idea best.  I feel the RvR of having the pet turn on you at full damage during a fight is still too unacceptably high, even if it is offset by being able to AFK when not fighting.  Right now, if you absolutely NEED to afk during a fight, you can do so, at the loss of the pet.  I see this as a convenience issue more than anything.
<br />

<br />
I did not come up with this idea, but it basically works like this.  Casting charm on a mob adds a high frequency proc to the pet, simililar to how NDT adds a lifetap proc.  This proc goes off at about the same frequency as the cleric hammer, and adds a debuff to the pet called "Confused Loyalties" that lasts 2-3 ticks.  It can't be dispelled, and it renews itself with every proc.  This debuff makes the pet hit at its alternate damage table for the duration of the debuff.  When charm breaks, or the pet is not attacking, the debuff wears off.  This means when charm breaks, as long as the pet has been attacking recently, the pet will remain at its "gimped damage" for a couple ticks after charm breaks, reducing, but not eliminating, the risk, for a short period of time.  Since the mob is debuffed already, no slows would be allowed to stack with it of course.  This would prevent the mob from becoming significantly weaker than it already is.
<br />

<br />
One might say this is exploitable, but I don't think 910 mana is very mana efficient for a 12 second debuff, especially compared to the slow lines.  Of course this wouldn't work against nameds either, since they can't be charmed.</span><span class="postbody"></span><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
                        </tr>
                </table></td>
        </tr>
