                        <tr>
                                <td colspan="2"><span class="postbody">The suggestion methods to prevent this abuse aside - it's not even a factor imo. If using charm as a debuff for a specific unique named mob is an issue, flag that one mob immune. I cant think of a mob where that would come into play though.
<br />

<br />
If someone is using 800+ mana spells to get common xp mobs weakened for 2-3 ticks as a means of being able to kill them where before they could not kill them, they have have to learn alot about efficiency. You get more milage out of a paladin just stunning the mob twice (negating it's damage entirely for that time). You can just "reverse charm" the mob instead of using charm as a debuff then doing the damage conventionally. The actual ingame usefulness of this abuse doesnt exist imo.
<br />

<br />
So yes there is definitely the potential for abuse with this solution unless a countermeasure is implemented alongside it - but no problem, just implement said solution too. And even without preventing the potential abuse, I doubt that there's a realistic way to actually gain an advantage with it.</span><span class="postbody"><br />_________________<br /><a href="http://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=7110" target="_blank" class="postlink">Jennifer DeGartes</a>, Enchantress of <a href="http://www.vazaelle.dk" target="_blank" class="postlink">Caer Cadarn</a></span><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
                        </tr>
